      <title>Scientists genetically modify rare fruit</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANScientists have come up with a way to modify a rare fruit and make it more accessible to the public.Researchers have genetically modified ground cherries to be larger and easier to grow than those found in the wild, according to a study published in Nature Plants.Ground cherries are usually found in South America as well as Central America, and are as small as a marble.The researchers involved described the taste of the fruit as "tropical yet sour" with a slight hint of vanilla.Ground cherries are also referred to as an "orphan crop" as it is grown on a small scale, but are difficult to produce enough to sell commercially as they often fall onto the ground before they are fully ripe.Scientists used CRISPR, a gene editing tool, to target a gene known as CLAVATA 1 to increase the size of the fruit, which resulted in the fruit becoming 25 percent heavier.Scientists also plan to edit the self-pruning gene found in the ground cherry to stop the plants shoots from continuing to grow once the fruit is ripe.The researchers hope this will help make ground cherries more appealing to the public, as well as inspire other scientists to genetically modify other rare fruits.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Wild ground cherries and genetically modified ground cherries. 2. Map of where ground cherries are typically found.3. DNA of ground cherry is seen being edited.4. Ground cherries in the wild with weeds.VOICEOVER (in English): "According to a study published in Nature Plants, researchers have genetically modified ground cherries to be larger and easier to grow than those found in the wild.""Ground cherries are usually found in South America as well as Central America, and are as small as a marble.""Scientists used CRISPR, a gene editing tool, to target a gene known as CLAVATA 1 to increase the size of the fruit, which resulted in the fruit becoming 25 percent heavier.""Scientists also plan to edit the self-pruning gene found in the ground cherry to stop the plants shoots from continuing to grow once the fruit is ripe."SOURCES: USA Today, CNN, Nature Plants, Tech Times, The Independent, https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2018/10/03/groundcherry-fruit-aided-crispr-could-hit-grocery-stores/1508764002/https://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/01/health/groundcherry-berry-study/index.html?utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=feed&utm_campaign=Feed%3A+rss%2Fcnn_health+%28RSS%3A+CNN+-+Health%29https://www.nature.com/articles/s41477-018-0259-x.epdf?referrer_access_token=8mRTSwY1DVWXX1SS5QJj9NRgN0jAjWel9jnR3ZoTv0N8w9A4jWVUi2o0SRzjtUigPgMhoJm73dU3FKjzK8DYx9mZxDB-fwOOrJ8tRdUlbnlf1pcUNkFmr_755ufKACsNVEVLy1NrApNXBlvE4hSTZLZ1CaQDwHNRRokDpiUkJIkkQyiVNz6vRpNT2kKBwDCjKi2a_W5EC9IWKfS0bG0_pPSkLNkY7WtLzht_MmipXsEbhMTEtNf6OGlRT8L5Nb3gHHAuAF6a7KZ3WGYZ29bVRji9oTTyJD6Ink5GOswQI1-tvZBC6ptMbF8T7bB5B1BpQWnTcOS70vM-Wrr5E52idao0eWIdrxYmkg6uNWkGO18Opwze6EKgqSy1zYFHF3prbRU9te6wPXCwlSe_-oPpkQ%3D%3D&tracking_referrer=edition.cnn.comhttps://www.techtimes.com/articles/234806/20181003/scientists-want-to-use-gene-editing-to-turn-wild-groundcherry-into-the-next-strawberry.htmhttps://www.independent.co.uk/news/science/groundcherry-fruit-gene-editing-berries-strawberries-physalis-a8563276.html***]]></description>
