      <title>New study finds microplastics in 90% of salt</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANResearchers from South Korea and Greenpeace East Asia have found that 90 percent of table salt sold around the world are contaminated with microplastics.After analyzing salt from 21 countries in Europe, Asia, North and South America, and Africa, a new study published in Environmental Science and Technology found microplastics in 36 out of 39 brands.Microplastic density was highest among Asian brands, especially those from Indonesia. The only three salts free from plastic were those from Taiwan, China, and France.Researchers sampled three types of salts and found that sea salt had the highest microplastic levels, followed by lake salt, and then rock salt.With particles often less than 5 millimeters in size and many the same color as salt, and they are barely noticeable.The study estimates that the average adult consumes 2,000 microplastics a year through salt.Scientists have yet to determine how harmful microplastics are to our bodies, but so far, experiments on mice haven't exactly brought good news.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. 36 out of 39 brands of salt found to contain microplastics2. Salt from Taiwan, China, France free from plastic3. Sea salt has highest microplastic level4. Average adult consumes 2,000 microplastics in a year from saltVOICEOVER (in English): "After analyzing salt from 21 countries in Europe, Asia, North and South America, and Africa, a new study found microplastics in 36 out of 39 brands.""Microplastic density was highest among Asian brands, especially those from Indonesia. The only three salts free from plastic were those from Taiwan, China, and France. ""Researchers sampled three types of salts and found that sea salt had the highest microplastic levels, followed by lake salt, and then rock salt.""The study estimates that the average adult consumes 2,000 microplastics a year through salt."SOURCES: Environmental Science and Technology, National Geographichttps://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acs.est.8b04180https://www.nationalgeographic.com/environment/2018/10/microplastics-found-90-percent-table-salt-sea-salt/?user.testname=none***]]></description>
