      <title>Cruise ship spills food waste onto the Great Barrier Reef</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANThe Australian Maritime Safety Authority has found that a cruise ship dumped 27,000 liters of food waste and gray water into the Great Barrier Reef in August.The cruise spilled the polluted water into the reef on August 26, but authorities weren't notified until two days later when the cruise reported the incident themselves.The cruise was detained by Australian authorities once it returned to Sydney. The ship had to pay a fine of US$1.5 million, CNN reported.The cruise says the spill was unintentional and claim they only dumped 7,000 liters instead of the 27,000 liters.However an Australian Senator cited an Australian Maritime Safety Authority report that says otherwise.Discharging waste into the Barrier Reef is a serious offense as the coral reefs in the region are already being damaged due to climate change and environmental damage.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Cruise ship dumping waste into the water2. Waste in the water3. Cruise ship docking and a stack of US dollars4. The waste affecting the coral reef VOICEOVER (in English): "The Australian Maritime Safety Authority has found that a cruise ship has dumped 27,000 liters of food waste and gray water into the Great Barrier Reef in August.""The cruise spilled the polluted water into the reef on August 26, however authorities weren't notified until two days later when the cruise reported the incident themselves.""According to reports from CNN, the cruise was detained by Australian authoritiesonce it returned to Sydney. The ship had to pay a fine of $1.5 million USD.""Discharging waste into the Barrier Reef is a serious offense as the coral reefs in the region are already being damaged due to climate change and environmental damage."SOURCES: CNN, The Guardian, Xinhuahttps://edition.cnn.com/2018/10/23/health/cruise-ship-spills-waste-in-great-barrier-reef-trnd/index.htmlhttps://www.theguardian.com/environment/2018/oct/22/po-cruise-ship-dumped-27000-litres-of-waste-on-great-barrier-reef-senate-hearshttp://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-10/23/c_137552171.htm***]]></description>
