      <title>Why baby bumps are bigger at night</title>
      <description><![CDATA[For story suggestions or custom animation requests, contact tips@nextanimation.com.tw. Visit http://archive.nextanimationstudio.com to view News Direct's complete archive of 3D news animations.RESTRICTIONS: Broadcast: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWAN Digital: NO USE JAPAN, NO USE TAIWANBaby bumps can change in size and shape in as little as a few hours, and have been known to appear larger at night than during the day.Birth doula Susannah Birch told Trimester Talk that abdominal muscles holding the baby bump become tired as the day goes on, causing them to loosen up. This allows the bump to expand and sit out further, thus appearing bigger.The muscles recuperate during sleep, and become refreshed and better able to maintain the bump's position in the morning.Levels of the hormone relaxin, which causes abdominal muscle stretching during pregnancy, was also found to be highest at night, according to a study published in the Handbook of Biologically Active Peptides.Women's Health reports that pregnant bellies have also been known to "pop" seemingly overnight, which is caused by the uterus expanding due to the growing fetus, and rising above the pubic bone. For most women, this tends to happen at around 10 to 12 weeks.RUNDOWN SHOWS:1. Abdominal muscles loosen as the day goes on, making baby bump look bigger 2. Muscles recuperate at night, maintain bump position in the morning3. Levels of hormone that loosens muscles highest at night4. Pregnant belly popping out once uterus rises above pubic bone VOICEOVER (in English): "Abdominal muscles holding the baby bump become tired as the day goes on, causing them to loosen up. This allows the bump to sit out further and appear bigger.""The muscles recuperate during sleep, and become refreshed and better able to maintain the bump's position in the morning.""Levels of the hormone relaxin, which causes abdominal muscle stretching during pregnancy, was also found to be highest at night.""Pregnant bellies have been known to 'pop' seemingly overnight, which is caused by the uterus expanding due to the growing fetus, and rising above the pubic bone."SOURCES: Trimester Talk, Women's Health, MSNhttps://trimestertalk.com/pregnant-belly-bigger-night/https://www.womenshealthmag.com/life/a19936546/pregnant-belly-pop/https://www.msn.com/en-ca/lifestyle/lifestyleroyals/the-weird-reason-meghan-markles-baby-bump-appears-larger-at-night/ar-BBOQdJS***]]></description>
